Thread : A thread represents a separate path of execution of a group of statements.

Which thread always runs in a java program by default => main thread

A thread represents execution of statements.
two types => 1. Single tasking 2. Multi tasking

1.Single Tasking :
    only one task given to the processer at a time.
    a lot of processor time and microprocess has to sit idle

2.Multi Tasking : fast switching between tasks.The system switches between tasks very fast, so it appears like they are running at the same time.
    Round Robin is used to share CPU time fairly among processes.
    Each process gets a fixed time slice called a time quantum / time slice.
    The CPU executes one process for that time.
    If the process is not finished, it goes to the back of the queue.
    The next process gets its turn.
    This continues in a circular order.
    Example:
    Processes: P1, P2, P3
    Time quantum = 2 units

    Execution order:
    P1 → P2 → P3 → P1 → P2 → … until all are completed

 * if we really want to achieve the multi tasking, we need computers with multiple processors.


Two types of multi Tasking :
    Process-based multitasking runs multiple independent programs with separate memory,
    while thread-based multitasking runs multiple threads within the same process sharing memory, making it faster but less safe.
1.Process based
    Multiple processes (independent programs) run concurrently.
    Each process has its own memory space
    Processes are isolated from each other
    Communication is slower (uses IPC like pipes, sockets)
    Pros:
        More secure & stable (one crash doesn’t affect others)
    Cons:
        Heavyweight (more memory & CPU overhead)
        Slower context switching
2.Thread based
    Multiple threads within the same process run concurrently.
    Threads share the same memory
    Faster communication (no need for IPC)
    Lightweight and efficient
    Example:
        A web server handling multiple requests
        One app doing background tasks + UI simultaneously
    Pros:
        Fast & efficient
        Better CPU utilization
    Cons:
        Less safe (one thread crash can affect entire process)
        Issues like race conditions, deadlocks

Question : Why thread are called light weight => because they utilize minimum resources of the system.
                                                 take less memory and less processor time

For Methods of thread see ThreadDemo class with explanation
T.start() => starts running the code inside the run() method

Terminating the thread : A thread terminate automatically when it comes out of run().or we need to write our on logic
    example in ThreadDemo.


MultiTasking using Threads:
    we can take multiple threads and attach them to the tasks and those tasks are simultaneously executed by the multiple threads
    and this is called multithreading.
    Example: MultiThreadingDemo file


Thread Synchronization or Thread safe: Preventing the threads to act on the same object simultaneously. this is called synchronization.

    t1
 ---------------------------|---------> ----|
                             |              |
                             |              |mutex
  t2 want till t1 come out   |              |
 ------------>               |______________|

Two type of Synchronize the object
    1.using synchronized block:
    2.Using synchronized Keyword
    Synchronized block locks only a specific section of code and is more efficient,
    while synchronized method locks the entire method and is simpler but less flexible.

    Use synchronized block 👉 in real projects (better performance)
    Use synchronized method 👉 for simple cases



Deadlock in Threads:
    A deadlock is a situation where two or more threads are stuck forever, each waiting for a resource that another thread holds.



Thread Life Cycle Diagram:
        +--------+
        |  NEW   |
        +--------+
             |
             | start()
             v
       +------------+
       | RUNNABLE   |  <----+
       +------------+       |
             |              |
             | (CPU picks)  |
             v              |
       +------------+       |
       |  RUNNING   |       |
       +------------+       |
        /    |     \        |
       /     |      \       |
      v      v       v      |
+---------+ +---------+ +-------------+
| BLOCKED | | WAITING | | TIMED WAIT |
+---------+ +---------+ +-------------+
     |           |            |
     +-----------+------------+
                 |
                 v
           +------------+
           | RUNNABLE   |
           +------------+
                 |
                 v
           +------------+
           | TERMINATED |
           +------------+

